<h2>Recent Research Topics (<a href="https://dblp.uni-trier.de/pid/86/2159.html">Full Publications (DBLP)</a> and <a href="https://github.com/HKUST-KnowComp">KnowComp Group Code</a>):</h2>
My research goal is to use machines to understand human languages and eventually facilitate natural human language interaction and communication. Our current approach is to extract useful knowledge from existing resources to construct knowledge graphs and use knowledge graphs to do reasoning and inference for understanding. When meeting downstream applications, we also need to care about privacy, security, and fairness issues to build trustworthy real-world systems.

<ul>
	<li><strong>Knowledge graph/base construction (<a href="http://home.cse.ust.hk/~yqsong/papers/WWW-Tutorial-Part4.pdf">New Trends</a>)</strong>

	<ul>
		<li><a href="https://haixun.github.io/probase.html">ProBase</a>: A concept knowledge graph extracted from billions of Web pages (<a href="https://concept.research.microsoft.com/">latest version</a>)</li>
		<li><a href="https://hkust-knowcomp.github.io/ASER">ASER</a>: An eventuality knowledge graph of activities, states, events, and their relations</li>
		<ul>
			<li><a href="https://github.com/HKUST-KnowComp/TransOMCS">TransOMCS</a>: Population of a commonsense knowledge base in the format of OMCS transferred from linguistic patterns in ASER</li>
			<li><a href="https://github.com/HKUST-KnowComp/DISCOS-commonsense">DISCOS</a>: Population of ATOMIC if-then inferential commonsense knowledge base with the discourse relations in ASER (<a href="https://github.com/HKUST-KnowComp/CSKB-Population">Extension: CSKB Population Benchmark</a>)</li>
		</ul>
		<li><a href="https://github.com/HKUST-KnowComp/atomic-conceptualization">AbstractATOMIC</a>: A conceptualization framework of commonsense knowledge aquisition and its resulting abstract knowledge in the form of ATOMIC</li>
		<li><a href="https://github.com/HKUST-KnowComp/AbsPyramid">AbsPyramid</a>: An implementation driven by Marvin Minsky's K-Line theory; a unification of entity typing, event typing, conceptualization, and entailment graphs</li>
		<li><a href="https://github.com/HKUST-KnowComp/AutoSchemaKG">AutoSchemaKG</a>: A framework to automatically extract entity, event, and perform conceptualization at Web scale, with three large examples: ATLAS-Wiki (from Wikipedia), ATLAS-Pes2o (from academic papers), and ATLAS-CC (from Common Crawl)</li>
		<li><a href="https://github.com/HKUST-KnowComp/MARS">MARS</a>: A metaphysical reasoning knowledge base</li>
		<li><a href="https://github.com/HKUST-KnowComp/FolkScope">FolkScope</a>: Eventuality-based intention knowledge graph for e-commerce commonsense understanding (later extented to <a href="https://www.amazon.science/blog/building-commonsense-knowledge-graphs-to-aid-product-recommendation">Amazon COSMO</a>)</li>
	</ul>
	</li>
	<li><strong>Natural language understanding and grounding to knowledge graphs</strong>
	<ul>
		<li>Conceptualization of the world knowledge</li>
		<li>Entity and event linking, semantic parsing, and discourse analysis</li>
	</ul>
	</li>
	<li><strong>Machine learning, inference, and reasoning with world knowledge</strong>
	<ul>
		<li>World knowledge representation, learning, and inference</li>
		<li>Learning with global structural world knowledge</li>
		<li>Neuro-symbolic inference and reasoning</li>
		<li>Neural graph database/knowledgebase systems</li>
	</ul>
	</li>
	<li><strong>Leveraging (commonsense) knowledge and social norms to improve privacy, security, explainability, and fairness issues in machine learning models for NLP</strong></li>
</ul>

